control_hassles: (1) Working at an in-bound customer service call center, I have no shortage of annoying customers to deal with.  Most recently, a customer called in to pay "the second half" of an order she had placed with us, and I had to advise her that we never actually received the first half of her payment.  I even checked with the sales agent who supposedly took it, and he confirmed that he ended up backing out of the transaction before completion because of an error (that could have easily been fixed, but that's neither here nor there.)  The customer claimed the payment was visible on her bank account, on her phone, as "pending," and I advised her that it would likely drop off soon; it will never get to the "processed" point because we didn't finish the payment.  However, I realized that this might have sounded fishy, and so I strongly suggested that she check with her bank first to confirm, if she wished.  Instead, she tried to argue with me for nearly half an hour about whether or not we took the payment, until finally escalating to a manager.  (2) I accidentally screwed up my budget because of a combination of underestimating bills and overestimating a small bonus I received unexpectedly, and now I'm having to cut back on food for the next week because of this error.  I only have myself to blame, unfortunately, but that doesn't make the situation any less frustrating.  (3) I've been buying "Magic: The Gathering" cards off eBay for the last two months, slowly building up a new "commander format" deck, as a hobby.  Once in a while, I'll check on the tracking of a card and find out that USPS has marked it as delivered, yet I can't find it anywhere around my apartment.  Usually, it shows up just fine the next day, (as is exactly what happened yesterday / today,) but it's still annoying to not know if the mailman delivered it to the wrong mailbox, or if he was just being lazy and marking stuff off as "delivered" without actually doing the work.  (4) I've been playing through Starcraft 2 on and off the last few days.  I love that sort of tatical, real-time-strategy format, but I hate how they tend to drop surprises in a way where it can be virtually impossible to win and the only solution is to restart a particular mission and then plan ahead for it.  I suppose, in a way, that does make the combat realistic, and I'm not opposed to "hard" games, but I dislike games that just seem designed to make you lose (unless you can somehow see the future.)  Often, they pair them with achievements that seem somewhat contradictory, such as asking the player to finish a mission in 15 minutes (basically rush your attacks on the enemy ASAP) but then also include a surprise ambush that can be impossible to defend against unless you've specifically taken the time to build up defenses in that area, (thus slowing your attack.)  (5) I'm annoyed that I can't seem to figure out how to make fried rice.  Granted, I've only attempted fried rice a few times, but it never turns out like it does in restaurants, and I'm not entirely sure why.  I tried it again last night, but ended up having to toss it and just go for regular steamed rice instead.

control_interesting:
In the past twenty-four hours, many simple things affected my emotions. First, I witnessed three hummingbirds fighting over the nectar I just put out for the morning. I found it fascinating because they come right up to me as I fill it and look me straight in the eyes, unaffected, and seemingly not threatened at all. They  make cute chirping noises. But whenever another hummingbird approaches to try to get to the feeder, they all become aggressive towards each other and chase each other off, oftentimes missing out on any of them getting to sip. Such cute creators that are so delicate and beautiful, yet to each other, they are mortal enemies. It just touched me to take time out of my day to study them and see the complicated relationship they have.

I also heard from a friend yesterday that I was missing so much that lives far away  who out of the blue called me and said he will be passing my way next weekend to see his daughter and he wants to spend time with me. It made me so happy, and like the gods or fate of the universe was favoring me. I am really excited to get to see him. I think he and I will always be close friends, and this time will be special.

I received a letter today that I was chosen to be in the "Who's Who of American Poetry" book and in the semi-finals in their poetry contest. That was good news and gave me a sense of pride.

My sister had cancer surgery this morning too, and it made me feel my own mortality. Cancer runs heavy in our family. I recently had a cancer scare that turned out to be benign "complicated cysts" and it was such a relief. But I was sad that my older sister had bad news and had to have the surgery. It just made me feel mixed emotions of being relieved of my results, but sad for hers and almost a sense of guilt that she has to go through this.

   I also have been improving a lot in my talent for art recently, and after illustrating many books for other people, I decided to fully illustrate my own, The decision felt emotional and right . I could not sleep from the excitement, and all I want to do now is to paint and draw all the time to get this book out.
